As far as bare g-C3N4 was concerned, normally, the photogenerated electron-hole pairs quickly recombined and only a fraction of them participated in water splitting reaction, resulting in low photocatalytic activity5,6,15,21. Based on the above analysis of the experiment and characterization results, the possible photocatalytic reaction mechanism and electron transfer processes of the g-C3N4/Ag2CrO4 nanocomposites were proposed (Fig. 8). The conduction band potential (ECB) and valence band potential (EVB) of the semiconductors could be calculated by the following empirical equations76:2ECB=X−Ee−12Eg\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
